\begin_layout Subsubsection
Probability Density Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normal distribution, which I refer to as 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

, describes a continuous variable that takes on values in the real number
 line.
 The two parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, determine the location and scale of the distribution.
 The probability density function is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x;\mu,\sigma^{2})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}}}\, e^{-\left(\frac{(x-\mu)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right)},\,-\infty<x<\infty.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The normalizing constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

, is required to assure that the area under the pdf will be 1.0.
 The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is, of course, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pi
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, roughly equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $3.14159\ldots$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is Euler's constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Greek letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mu
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sigma squared
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scale
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 parameter.
 In the literature, one will find the formula re-arranged in various ways,
 for example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x;\mu,\sigma^{2})=\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}\, e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}},\,\textnormal{or}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x;\mu,\sigma^{2})=\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}\, e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}(x-\mu)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make sense out of the pdf, concentrate on the kernel, the part that depends
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}(x-\mu)^{2}}\label{eq:NormalKernel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To simplify, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

 (making this a standard normal distribution, 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,1)$
\end_inset

).
 That leaves us with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{-\frac{1}{2}x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Throw away the fraction from the exponent, since it is a simple scaling
 factor.
 That means the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and its probability density is simple.
 We only need to understand
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e^{-x^{2}}\label{eq:NormalSimplifiedKernel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 move and stretch the shape, but they do not fundamentally change it.
 As illustrated above in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NormalKernel"

\end_inset

, that function is unimodal and symmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is thus a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

location parameter.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The peak of the normal distribution's density, its mode (most likely value),
 will always correspond with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The shape of the distribution is unaffected by a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 It simply shifts to the left or right, as illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
